            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.12.24"/>
                
                <note type="recipient">Prof. Katharine Lee Bates</note>
                
                <note type="recipient" place="margin">please return to me Jno.</note>
                
                <note type="recipient" place="top">Answered my Song <unclear>April</unclear> 71926</note>
                    
                <note type="recipient" place="right margin">5, 12 19 26 Oct., Nov 2, 9 afternoon</note>
                    
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">70 CURVE STREET
                        <lb/>
                    WELLESLEY
                        <lb/>
                    MASS.</hi>
                </fw>
                    
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Mar. 29, 1926.</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Is there any likelihood that you will be in the East next autumn and could come to Wellesley to give us a reading from your poems? For some years now we have been enabled through the income of a small fund to give a brief series of poem recitals in October and early November. We do not want lectures, though of course the poet is free to make such comment on his poems as he wishes. Personally, I am an enthusiastic admirer of your <hi rend="underline">Song of the Indian Wars</hi>, which I had the pleasure of reviewing for the New York Post last autumn, and I would like nothing better than to have you come before our students and read episodes from that deeply moving epic.</p>
                    
                <p>The highest payment we can make it $100, so of course we realize that we must take advantage of your coming to New York or Boston for other engagements. Our readings regularly fall on the four Tuesdays afternoons of October and the first <hi rend="underline">two of</hi> November. Can you give us any hope that you might be with us for one of these dates?</p> 
                    
                <p>Yours with warmest congratulations on the portions of your five-fold epic already accomplished.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Katharine Lee Bates</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
